title: "2015 Camry LE - Buying Process and Review",
date: "2015-02-12 01:25:16"
---

<a href=\"http:\/\/andrewdelosreyes.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/03\/20150127_170333.jpg\"><img class=\"alignleft wp-image-160 size-medium\" src=\"http:\/\/andrewdelosreyes.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/03\/20150127_170333-300x225.jpg\" alt=\"2015 Camry LE\" width=\"300\" height=\"225\" \/><\/a> Just bought a 2015 Camry LE. Here was a recap of my experience, and a short review of driving it through extreme weather conditions in Dallas.\r\n\r\n<strong>The Buying Process<\/strong>\r\n\r\nI actually started off in the market for a new or lightly used Corolla, for the cheaper price. I figured it would do the job of being a decent family car, with few option requirements from me. I also figured I'd spend around $18,000 on a new one, or perhaps around $14,000 on a used. <!--more Read post-->Then I came across this post about <a title=\"Jalopnik article on the 2014 Corolla\" href=\"http:\/\/jalopnik.com\/how-toyota-screwed-up-the-2014-toyota-corolla-1187863687\" target=\"_blank\">how Toyota screwed up the 2014 Corolla<\/a> and was a bit turned off. The tipping point was finding a dealer offering $4,000 off MSRP on new Camrys, and I was swayed to the better-model Toyota.\r\n\r\nLet me back track a bit. I actually started off using TrueCar to see what the lowest price points were on Corollas. I grabbed 3 certificates for guaranteed prices from TrueCar, and got to work emailing the dealers, asking them to tell me why I should buy from them. Then, hearing about the Camry special, I transitioned over from Corolla haggling to Camry haggling. My offer started off as being, I'll buy today if you give me an out-the-door price of $20,000, flat. Of course, they wouldn't do it, seeing as final closing costs could bring the price as high as $24,000 and up for a base Camry. Going back and forth, I settled with the dealer (all via email, mind you) for $21.5 out-the-door.\r\n\r\nProblem is, that dealer was over an hour away from me. There was a Toyota dealer 5 minutes away, so you bet I took his quote to them and asked if they wanted to try and beat it. Long story short, I got out of there with a 2015 Camry at $21,750 out-the-door, with tinted windows and special mats (whatever). I believe I got a great deal, but if you know better, feel free to tell me I'm wrong!\r\n\r\n<strong>A month out, how is she driving?<\/strong>\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"attachment_158\" align=\"alignright\" width=\"300\"]<a href=\"http:\/\/andrewdelosreyes.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/03\/10885122_10152646968102093_5516020701960241268_n.jpg\"><img class=\"wp-image-158 size-medium\" src=\"http:\/\/andrewdelosreyes.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/03\/10885122_10152646968102093_5516020701960241268_n-300x202.jpg\" alt=\"Dallas Traffic during Sleetmaggedon\" width=\"300\" height=\"202\" \/><\/a> A map of how bad traffic and accidents got when the roads iced over.[\/caption]\r\n\r\nThe past couple of weeks has been hectic in Dallas, in terms of weather. We've faced two days of Sleetmaggedon, and another couple of days of snow and ice on the roads. Tons of accidents, tons of drivers getting stuck on the road. This turned into an excellent opportunity to test out the Camry's capabilities in poor conditions. I was interested in particular how the traction control would fare. I didn't stress test it by any means, but I was able to get a good feel for the Camry's normal driving limits.\r\n\r\nOut of 4 days driving through ice and snow, I felt the brakes lock once for about 2-3 seconds when cars in front of me suddenly stopped on the freeway. I kept my distance and was going about 35mph, so I had time to experience the lock, regain control and still stop the car well before it was too late. Traction control kicked in and helped me out pretty quickly, but it may not have been quick enough had I been going faster or been closer to the cars ahead of me. Apart from that incident, no other locking or slipping, apart from intentionally gunning it to feel it out. The only thing I don't like is how the traction control light flashes in bright red when it kicks in, and paying attention to it would seem to give someone an anxiety attack, rather than allow them to focus on regaining control. But I don't have a better solution for how that could be.\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"attachment_161\" align=\"alignleft\" width=\"225\"]<a href=\"http:\/\/andrewdelosreyes.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/03\/20150227_100540.jpg\"><img class=\"wp-image-161 size-medium\" src=\"http:\/\/andrewdelosreyes.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/03\/20150227_100540-225x300.jpg\" alt=\"2015 Camry LE in the Snow\" width=\"225\" height=\"300\" \/><\/a> Camry's first snow day.[\/caption]\r\n\r\nThe Camry also did well accelerating uphill in icy conditions, and did not lose traction at all. Rear wheel drive cars ahead of me were having trouble regaining traction after having stopped, but the good ol' Camry had no issues making it up whatsoever. The highest incline I went up was about 40% grade, which was enough to keep an old Tacoma and a Mustang ahead of me spinning helplessly. I flipped my signal and passed right on by in the next lane.\r\n\r\n<strong>New features - well, new to me<\/strong>\r\n\r\nWhen shopping, I was ready to tell the dealers to forget selling options to me, because I wasn't interested. I thought myself a simple guy who could do more with less. However, after you purchase, it's the little things that really make for a great experience. I'll only mention two things that I enjoy on my new Camry that I didn't have in my previous car. They aren't unique to it, but not all cars come equipped with them, either.\r\n\r\nFirst are the <strong>side mirror heaters<\/strong>. No better time to appreciate these than during the DFW sleet and snowstorms. Instead of having to work to free my mirrors of icy buildup, all I had to do was hit the button, wait a few minutes, and voila - the mirrors are clear. It seems like a small thing, but man is it impressive.\r\n\r\nSecond is the <strong>touch screen<\/strong> with blue tooth capability and the back up camera. Talking on the phone while driving is legal in Texas, but it's still not a good idea with all the loonies on the road. But with your phone connected to the car's blue tooth, talking and driving is a piece of cake. And that back up camera is nothing short of amazing when you're parallel parking and need to know how far away you are from the car behind you (that's really the only time I depend on it). Gone are the days when I needed my passenger to get out and direct me when trying to fit into a tight spot downtown. The camera helps you get it right every time.\r\n\r\n<strong>Conclusion<\/strong>\r\n\r\nOverall, I'm really happy with the purchase and would definitely go for the Camry as a reliable family car, every time. I plan to have the car 20 years or more, keeping up with regular maintenance and doing whatever repairs I need to as they come. They are easy to work on and inexpensive to maintain, and that's enough to keep me a Toyota fan for a very long time.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;


