title: "Fixing the valve cover leak on a 2004 Suzuki Forenza once and for all - gasket replacement",
date: "2015-03-05 04:29:20"
---

For a while now I've known my Forenza had an oil leak. My dad has tried at least once to fix it by changing the valve cover gasket, but was convinced Suzuki simply manufactured a crappy valve cover that leaked. Well, I got around to giving it another shot last weekend, and so far the valve cover does not leak. <!--more-->\r\n\r\n<strong>If you've already done some research and\/or tried to fix yours, here's what the solution was: my dad read somewhere that putting gasket maker on both points of contact, being between the gasket and the valve cover, and between the gasket and the engine block, would do the trick. For some reason, that did not fix the oil leak. What I did differently was I put gasket maker only between the gasket and the valve cover, NOT on the engine block at all. So currently the gasket is directly seated onto the engine block, and so far it is not leaking at all.<\/strong>\r\n\r\nFor those who are replacing for the first time, I'll continue. Here's all you need:\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li>A 10mm wrench for the valve cover bolts<\/li>\r\n\t<li>Pliers to remove the hoses<\/li>\r\n\t<li>Gasket maker (I used black, though countless others recommend gray)<\/li>\r\n\t<li>Replacement gasket (I bought an aftermarket one from eBay; didn't bother with OEM)<\/li>\r\n<\/ul>\r\nFirstly, note that you do not need to drain your oil before changing the valve cover gasket. When you're ready, start\u00a0removing the hoses attached to the cover. There should be two on the side facing the car, and one facing you.\r\n\r\nTake an allen wrench and pull off the top cover by unscrewing the two bolts on top. This will expose the other end of your spark plug wires. When it's off, it will look like this:\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http:\/\/andrewdelosreyes.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/02\/IMG_0073.jpg\"><img class=\"alignleft wp-image-81 size-full\" src=\"http:\/\/andrewdelosreyes.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/02\/IMG_0073.jpg\" alt=\"Suzuki Forenza Valve Cover Replacement\" width=\"2048\" height=\"1536\" \/><\/a>\r\n\r\nTake note of the sequence of the spark plug wires (take a picture to be safe) before you pull them out. You will need to put them back in exactly the same order. Remove these wires and set them aside. If your valve cover leak is bad enough, you may have oil inside the spark plug wells, like mine. If you do, be ready to clean this out, because oil here will cause the cylinders to misfire.\r\n\r\nNext, remove the ten bolts holding the valve cover in place. Set these aside. This is what it will look like with the valve cover off.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http:\/\/andrewdelosreyes.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/02\/20150207_121732.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-82\" src=\"http:\/\/andrewdelosreyes.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/02\/20150207_121732.jpg\" alt=\"Suzuki Forenza Valve Cover Removed\" width=\"612\" height=\"816\" \/><\/a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nNow you've got some cleaning work to do. You want to clean both the engine block where your valve cover will have contact, as well as he valve cover. You can see mine in the video below, including what it looks like when you have applied gasket maker to the inside of the cover. At this point mine still had the gasket inside, that needed to be pulled out and then cleaned up.\r\n\r\n<iframe src=\"https:\/\/www.youtube.com\/embed\/VAu0hNxrwiI\" width=\"560\" height=\"315\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen=\"allowfullscreen\"><\/iframe>\r\n\r\nOnce everything is all cleaned up, get your new gasket ready and open up that gasket maker. If this is your first time, you may want to try putting the gasket in dry so that you can see how it goes in. Go ahead and apply a thin line of gasket maker to the valve cover where the gasket will go. I did this one section at a time, so that the gasket maker wouldn't dry up on me before I was ready, but you\u00a0should be good with doing it all at once if you've got a steady hand. When you're done applying the gasket maker, press the gasket into the grooves, and clean up any gasket maker that oozes out.\r\n\r\nWhen you've got the engine block cleaned up where the gasket will seat, you're ready to place your valve cover back on. <strong>Important<\/strong>: if you did end up having oil in your spark plug wells, now would be a great time to clean it all out. I tried using a baster, but it didn't suck out all of the oil. I ended up using Q-tips to soak up the oil, and it got everything nice and dry. Also, make sure you don't let anything get into your engine while it is open. When ready, place the valve cover on and hand tighten the bolts back on. Now, there does exist a proper order to put the bolts back on, as well as a specific torque to torque them down, and of course, this is the way to go if you have the manual and want to do things 100% to the book. For the record, I did not consult the manual and put the bolts back on in a criss-cross fashion. After hand tightening the bolts, I tightened them down with a socket wrench and left them \"hand tight\". It is important that you do not overtighten these bolts as this could cause the valve cover to leak again. Get them tight, but not too tight, and you should be good.\r\n\r\nWhen you're done, put everything back together in reverse order, and you're finished! Let the gasket maker cure before you start the car up again. I let it sit for about 14 hours before I drove it again. Your valve cover should now be leak-free!


