title: "AEM Beginner Overview - Wrapping My Head Around My Setup",
date: "2015-03-07 00:34:53"
---

One of my latest projects involves building a site using Adobe's content management system. With no technical degree and no previous training, this has really taken me a while to wrap my head around. After being thrown to the wolves, I think I am beginning to get the hang of how it works. <!--more Read post-->\r\n\r\nHere are the major players in this game:\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li>My local drive<\/li>\r\n\t<li>My local AEM instance<\/li>\r\n\t<li>Brackets Sightly Extension<\/li>\r\n\t<li>Maven<\/li>\r\n\t<li>My remote repository<\/li>\r\n\t<li>My remote AEM instance<\/li>\r\n\t<li>Git<\/li>\r\n<\/ul>\r\nAll of this got thrown at me, and none of it was familiar. Here's how I understand it works:\r\n<ol>\r\n\t<li>I can develop directly in my local files, but they will not affect my local instance (unless I am using the Sightly Extension, which will automatically update my AEM instance as I work and save my files).<\/li>\r\n\t<li>To get what's on my local drive into my AEM instance, I use Maven. Maven will build a package with my local files, and upload and install them for me. Then I will be able to see the changes on the site locally.<\/li>\r\n\t<li>To get everything onto the remote server, first I need to push my files to it using Git.<\/li>\r\n\t<li>Once everything is kosher on the repository, Maven can then be used to transfer everything to the remote AEM instance. Then updates can be seen on the public site (in short).<\/li>\r\n\t<li>For ongoing development, when writing new code, first I'll need to update my local files by pulling what others have pushed to the repository (this is actually before step 1).<\/li>\r\n<\/ol>\r\nAnd that's the basic overview of, I suppose, one setup of AEM. I only wish it had been explained to me in laymen's terms beforehand!


