title: "Engine Coolant Thermostat Replacement, 2004 Suzuki Forenza",
date: "2015-04-03 22:37:26"
---

Replacing this thermostat on your Forenza is fairly simple, seeing as it's located right in front in an easy to get to location. All you will need is the replacement thermostat, which comes inside its housing, a few tools, and a pan to drain your coolant.\r\n<ol>\r\n\t<li><a href=\"#stepone\">Drain the coolant<\/a><\/li>\r\n\t<li><a href=\"#steptwo\">Remove hose and faulty thermostat<\/a><\/li>\r\n\t<li><a href=\"#stepthree\">Install the new thermostat<\/a><\/li>\r\n\t<li><a href=\"#stepfour\">Reattach hose and replace coolant<\/a><\/li>\r\n<\/ol>\r\n<section><\/section><!--more Read post-->\r\n\r\n<section><\/section><section id=\"stepone\"><strong>1. Drain the coolant<\/strong><\/section><section>Open your coolant reservoir. Then, locate your drain plug screw on the bottom of the radiator, which should be right behind the front bumper. You shouldn't need to lift your car to do it. Place your drain pan underneath the hole that lines up with the drain plug screw and slowly unscrew the plug. The fluid will start to flow through the hole. Sit tight and let it drain. When it's done, set it aside somewhere where stuff can't fall in (if you plan to put the same fluid back in), or dispose of it.<\/section><section>\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"attachment_192\" align=\"alignleft\" width=\"2448\"]<a href=\"http:\/\/andrewdelosreyes.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/04\/20150323_182332.jpg\"><img class=\"wp-image-192 size-full\" src=\"http:\/\/andrewdelosreyes.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/04\/20150323_182332-e1428541844489.jpg\" alt=\"Radiator drain plug screw, Suzuki Forenza\" width=\"2448\" height=\"2129\" \/><\/a> View of the drain plug screw from beneath the front bumper.[\/caption]\r\n\r\n<\/section><section id=\"steptwo\"><strong>2. Remove hose and faulty thermostat<\/strong><\/section><section>Remove the hose that connects the radiator to the faulty thermostat, and push it aside. Unscrew the bolts attaching the sensor to the engine block. Pull the thermostat off.<\/section><section><a href=\"http:\/\/andrewdelosreyes.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/04\/20150323_184821.jpg\"><img class=\"alignleft wp-image-193 size-full\" src=\"http:\/\/andrewdelosreyes.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/04\/20150323_184821.jpg\" alt=\"Removing the hose connected to engine coolant sensor\" width=\"3264\" height=\"2448\" \/><\/a><\/section><section><\/section><section id=\"stepthree\"><strong>3. Install the new thermostat<\/strong><\/section><section>Clean off the surface on the engine where the old sensor was. Then, install the new sensor (with gasket that comes with it). Do not overtighten!<\/section><section class=\"inline-img\"><a href=\"http:\/\/andrewdelosreyes.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/04\/20150323_185528.jpg\"><img class=\"alignleft wp-image-196 size-full\" src=\"http:\/\/andrewdelosreyes.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/04\/20150323_185528.jpg\" alt=\"Old engine coolant sensor\" width=\"3264\" height=\"2448\" \/><\/a><\/section><section class=\"inline-img\"><a href=\"http:\/\/andrewdelosreyes.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/04\/20150323_181624.jpg\"><img class=\"alignleft wp-image-191 size-full\" src=\"http:\/\/andrewdelosreyes.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/04\/20150323_181624.jpg\" alt=\"New Engine Coolant Sensor\" width=\"3264\" height=\"2448\" \/><\/a><\/section><section id=\"stepfour\"><strong><a href=\"http:\/\/andrewdelosreyes.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/04\/20150323_181621.jpg\"><img class=\"alignleft wp-image-190 size-full\" src=\"http:\/\/andrewdelosreyes.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/04\/20150323_181621.jpg\" alt=\"New Engine Coolant Sensor View\" width=\"3264\" height=\"2448\" \/><\/a><\/strong><\/section><section><\/section><section><\/section><section><\/section><section><\/section><section><\/section><section><\/section><section><\/section><section><\/section><section><\/section><section><\/section><section><\/section><section><\/section><section><\/section><section><\/section><section><\/section><section><\/section><section>\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"attachment_195\" align=\"alignleft\" width=\"3264\"]<a href=\"http:\/\/andrewdelosreyes.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/04\/20150323_185053.jpg\"><img class=\"wp-image-195 size-full\" src=\"http:\/\/andrewdelosreyes.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/04\/20150323_185053.jpg\" alt=\"Socket to remove thermostat housing bolt\" width=\"3264\" height=\"2448\" \/><\/a> Here's the socket I used to remove the bolts.[\/caption]\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"attachment_197\" align=\"alignleft\" width=\"3264\"]<a href=\"http:\/\/andrewdelosreyes.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/04\/20150323_190019.jpg\"><img class=\"wp-image-197 size-full\" src=\"http:\/\/andrewdelosreyes.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/04\/20150323_190019.jpg\" alt=\"Engine coolant thermostat removed\" width=\"3264\" height=\"2448\" \/><\/a> Engine coolant thermostat removed.[\/caption]\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"attachment_198\" align=\"alignleft\" width=\"3264\"]<a href=\"http:\/\/andrewdelosreyes.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/04\/20150323_191311.jpg\"><img class=\"wp-image-198 size-full\" src=\"http:\/\/andrewdelosreyes.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/04\/20150323_191311.jpg\" alt=\"New engine coolant thermostat in place\" width=\"3264\" height=\"2448\" \/><\/a> New engine coolant thermostat in place.[\/caption]\r\n\r\n<strong>4. Reattach hose and replace coolant<\/strong>\r\n\r\n<\/section><section>Put the hose back on where it was. Screw your drain plug back in. Replace coolant in the reservoir until you get to the line. Start the car and let it warm up. After the car has warmed up, shut it off, let it cool down and add more coolant until it gets to the line. Check the sensor and make sure it isn't leaking. You're done!<\/section><section><a href=\"http:\/\/andrewdelosreyes.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/04\/20150323_191938.jpg\"><img class=\"alignleft wp-image-199 size-large\" src=\"http:\/\/andrewdelosreyes.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/04\/20150323_191938-e1428541573314-1024x931.jpg\" alt=\"Coolant reservoir\" width=\"625\" height=\"568\" \/><\/a><\/section>


