I've had my Big Baby Taylor for less than a year now, and after switching strings I noticed my action was way too high to play comfortably. I tried switching the old ones back on, but\u00a0was still bothered by the action being higher than I'm used to. I tried lowering it by sanding the saddle down, but I got it to the point where my first E slot was nearly flush with the bridge and the action was still too high. Here's a before shot of the action on my guitar:\u00a0<!--more Read post-->\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignleft wp-image-213 size-full\" src=\"http:\/\/andrewdelosreyes.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/04\/20150426_145330-e1430111756393.jpg\" alt=\"Big Baby Taylor High Action\" width=\"612\" height=\"450\" \/>\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http:\/\/andrewdelosreyes.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/04\/20150426_145336.jpg\"><img class=\"alignleft wp-image-214 size-full\" src=\"http:\/\/andrewdelosreyes.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/04\/20150426_145336.jpg\" alt=\"Big Baby Taylor High Action, Saddle Nearly Flush\" width=\"3264\" height=\"2448\" \/><\/a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nI decided to\u00a0unscrew the neck where it is screwed onto the body, and raised it a millimeter or so using a credit card. Now the problem is solved and the difference in playability of my Big Baby Taylor is night and day.\r\n\r\nNow, I know you all you \"real guitar players\" out there will frown on something like this, and I've seen people suggest only adjusting the saddle height to lower action. Happy to hear all the success stories of a simple fix like that.\u00a0But just adjusting the saddle will not do it for this guitar - at least for mine. So if you're reading this and considering doing it, jus know that it is an unconventional way of solving this problem. If you're like me and do not care, then read on.\r\n\r\nFirst, you'll need to remove the strings. After loosening the strings, I took pliers and removed the pegs\u00a0attaching them to the body.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignleft wp-image-215 size-full\" src=\"http:\/\/andrewdelosreyes.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/04\/20150426_145439.jpg\" alt=\"Big Baby Taylor Removing Strings\" width=\"3264\" height=\"2448\" \/>\r\n\r\nNext, unscrew the two screws in the neck. Don't worry about the neck falling off - it should be pretty firmly attached, even with the screws out. You'll pull the neck off in the next step.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignleft wp-image-217 size-full\" src=\"http:\/\/andrewdelosreyes.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/04\/20150426_150125-e1430112720872.jpg\" alt=\"Unscrew the neck, Big Baby Taylor\" width=\"609\" height=\"477\" \/>\r\n\r\nHere's the tricky part. You'll want to remove the neck carefully, because at this point you can really damage your guitar if you're too rough. I pushed forward on the neck, with my hand near the head of the guitar. When that moved forward a couple of inches, I began to wedge it back and forth until it came out completely. It will take a big of muscle, but eventually it will come out.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http:\/\/andrewdelosreyes.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/04\/20150426_150228.jpg\"><img class=\"alignleft wp-image-224 size-full\" src=\"http:\/\/andrewdelosreyes.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/04\/20150426_150228-e1430112923938.jpg\" alt=\"Pulling off the neck, Big Baby Taylor Guitar\" width=\"605\" height=\"477\" \/><\/a>\r\n\r\nNow that it's off, set it aside and grab an old credit card. where the neck sits is just enough space to fit an entire credit card, or similar sized card. What you'll want to do is cut the card so that you have space for the screws to go through that area. I experimented a few ways, but eventually went with a large piece of the card beneath the screw holes, and a sliver of the card above the holes. I'd image you could just cut a square where the screw holes go.\r\n\r\nIt's important to do this step in a way that the neck will still fit on as flat as possible back onto the body. Your screws will fit on a certain way, so if the neck sits in the slot at even a slight angle, you will have problems getting it to stay put\u00a0once you put your strings back on.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http:\/\/andrewdelosreyes.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/04\/20150426_150608.jpg\"><img class=\"alignleft wp-image-220 size-full\" src=\"http:\/\/andrewdelosreyes.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/04\/20150426_150608-e1430113416230.jpg\" alt=\"Big Baby Taylor with a card in the neck slot\" width=\"599\" height=\"465\" \/><\/a>\r\n\r\nOnce you have the card cut the way you want it, wedge your neck back on, similar to the way you took it off. Be even more careful putting it back on, as you could break something during this step. The neck fits extremely snug, so make sure you've got the right angle and not too much force. Once it's flat, put the screws back in, and put a string back on to test the action. It should be adjusted to the right height with only one card, without getting vibration from the strings against the frets.\r\n\r\nIf at this point you realize that your saddle is now too low, you can adjust that by cutting a sliver from another credit card and putting it underneath the saddle. Or, of course, you could buy a new saddle.\r\n\r\nIf you did everything correctly and didn't break anything, at this point you'll be a happy camper with a much more playable Big Baby Taylor Guitar.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;


