My 1990 F150 was having trouble starting after it had already warmed up. It started fine when it was cold, but after driving it for 15 minutes or more and shutting it off, it would crank, but would have trouble turning over and running. I would have to wait 10 to 15 minutes to let it cool down, and then it would have enough juice to start.\r\n\r\nMy battery is still only 6 months old, so I knew there probably wasn't a problem with it. But looking under the hood, I noticed that, after trying over and over to start it, the material covering the negative battery cable had melted, about 3 inches from its connection to the terminal, exposing the wires inside. The positive cable was also a little frayed at the connection, but didn't seem too bad.\r\n\r\nLooking it up online, I learned that a bad electrical connection can cause the cables to overheat, and in my case, melt. The heat also worsens the connection, and makes it behave like a resistor. The result is that my starter was not getting adequate charge from my battery, even though there was nothing wrong with the battery.\r\n\r\nMy solution was to replace both the positive and negative battery cables. In addition, I added another ground, running from the negative battery terminal to the starter's ground point. The cable I used was 60 inches. The battery also has a ground from the negative terminal to the body, and another running down to the chassis.\r\n\r\nThe starter is located underneath the engine, at its rear. It looks like a fat canister with a smaller thing on top (may not be visible, depending on your angle). It will have a wire running from it all the way to the starter solenoid, on the side of the engine bay (your positive battery cable should also run to this). The ground point is at one of the bolts that fastens it, at the bottom. You can remove that bolt and install your wire. You may already have a ground wire running from it.\r\n\r\nAfter doing that, the truck starts up better than it ever has, hot or cold!\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"attachment_281\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"625\"]<a href=\"http:\/\/andrewdelosreyes.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/07\/20150716_182839.jpg\"><img class=\"size-large wp-image-281\" src=\"http:\/\/andrewdelosreyes.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/07\/20150716_182839-1024x768.jpg\" alt=\"1990 F150 Battery Cables, Fixing Warm Start Trouble\" width=\"625\" height=\"469\" \/><\/a> To fix problems with starting while the truck is warm, check the battery cables, replace if worn, and put proper grounds in place.[\/caption]\r\n\r\nI also read in the forum that people added a ground from the starter to the frame. Some already had this in place; my truck did not. I am also going to do this just in case. Apparently, you can never have too many grounds.\r\n\r\n<strong>References:<\/strong>\r\n\r\n<a href=\"https:\/\/answers.yahoo.com\/question\/index?qid=20081009054539AApTufU\">https:\/\/answers.yahoo.com\/question\/index?qid=20081009054539AApTufU<\/a>\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http:\/\/www.f150online.com\/forums\/pre-1997-models\/475590-negative-ground-battery-cable.html\">http:\/\/www.f150online.com\/forums\/pre-1997-models\/475590-negative-ground-battery-cable.html<\/a>


