title: "My Challenges as a New Homeowner",
date: "2016-12-13 23:30:12"
---

The reality that home ownership is a nightmare and a money suck is week by week etching itself into my mind. I am a not yet a month in and have already dealt with a handful of costly challenges that I never expected going into the deal. It appears everyone has their own seemingly unique set of issues to sort out, so there is no definitive list you could use to ensure all your \"T\"s are crossed and \"I\"s dotted. <!--more Read post-->\r\n\r\n<strong>1. Rats in the attic<\/strong>\r\n\r\nA week into moving out of our old place, my wife and I sat down at our dining table after a day of packing moving and cleaning around 10PM. All of a sudden we heard a scratching noise running up the wall and across the ceiling. We looked at each other, jaws dropped; we knew we had some sort of pest to deal with. I ran upstairs with a flashlight and open the hatch. Lo and behold, a rat was staring at me from the other side of the attic.\r\n\r\nAmong the different types of pest control methods attempted, what has worked so far are the standard wood and metal bar snap traps. I've killed two rats in them, and I'm certain a third is still hiding, avoiding the fate of its comrades. I may need to switch up the peanut butter and use something more enticing to catch this straggler.\r\n\r\n<strong>2. Plumbing\/Sewer Issues<\/strong>\r\n\r\nAbout a week after moving in, I began to smell some odd odor coming from the guest bathroom. Fast forward to this week, the smell is unbearable if the door is shut and the ventilation turned off. Something in there has gotten progressively worse.\r\n\r\nWe made a claim with our home warrant company, and they sent a plumber over to diagnose the issue yesterday. He noticed the wax seal under our toilet was nearly gone, so he replaced that. After waiting several hours and rechecking, the smell persisted. So that was $60 down the drain, and no skin off the home warranty company's back.\r\n\r\nAs of yesterday I finally found that most of the odor is coming from the bathtub drain, so I'm currently attempting to neutralize it with bleach. Really hoping to not have to do any major repairs.\r\n\r\n<strong>3. Created an account for water and electricity, but not gas<\/strong>\r\n\r\nOur furnace and water heater are run by gas, not electricity. I found that out two days ago when my wife texted me saying the heater wasn't working, and she couldn't get hot water. Called Atmos, and the soonest the can come out is tomorrow. So we are now on day two of no showers (it's 38 degrees F in Dallas at the moment), and the fireplace and space heaters are in full effect.\r\n\r\n<strong>4. Got\u00a0the wrong size refrigerator<\/strong>\r\n\r\nThis one was also completely my fault. The space between my counter and pantry will only take a 35\" wide refrigerator, and the one I got is 36\". Measuring should have been a no-brainer. Wise advice from a coworker: If you think it may kinda fit and you can just muscle it in, more than likely, it's not going to fit.\r\n\r\n<strong>5. Mold in my air ducts<\/strong>\r\n\r\nI'm not sure how this one got past inspection, but to their credit, you did have to remove the vent covers and shine a light inside in order to see the mold. Unfortunately, not catching this one had terrible consequences. Everyone in my house got sick, including my toddler and 4-month-old, and that persisted a good 2 weeks or so.\r\n\r\nAnother misfortune: mold remediation is expensive. What started out as a $100 duct cleaning turned into a $500 duct cleaning and mold removal.


