title: "Blog Every Day, Even If No One Reads (and working out)",
date: "2016-12-18 23:05:49"
---

Last week I attended Digital Summit, and the first keynote speaker was Seth Godin. Of the many quotes I was able to capture and tweet from his speech and Q&amp;A session, one was the title of this post. We should blog every day to get our head straight--something like that. So, here I am, taking his advice.<!--more Read post-->\r\n\r\nI was actually inspired to write regularly a couple weeks prior by Jordan Peterson, the professor at University of Toronto who has been in the news much lately. He believes that writing down thoughts and working out our issues through writing is not only effective, but also rewires our brain in positive ways. He hawked his Future Writing Program on his spot on Joe Rogan's podcast, and I got it online from his website free. For the past 15 years or so I haven't been the type to think heavily about my future, further than perhaps morw than 5 years at a time. I haven't started on the exercise yet so I'm not sure what to expect, but I do hope it turns out to be as rewarding as he said it would be.\r\n\r\nAll this has come, like most things in life seem to, at a timely moment where I feel more upside down than most others. I just bought a house and after two weeks am still a good 30% away from a decent completion point of my move; my wife and kids just got over being sick; my workout routine has lost its rhythm; my bedtime and waking time have gotten later and more taxing on my day. The latter two I consider the most concerning of them all; it seems once I lose my sleep and exercise patterns, the rest of the habits that keep me afloat start coming down one by one. It would seem to me a great time to stop and reconsider my life by means of writing, as suggested by these great thinkers and influencers.\r\n\r\nSaving other topics for other days, I'll dig into working out. It's the habit I've always strived to maintain, but have without fail always done in sprints of a few months and slowly given up. I'd say the first of these sprints began around 10th grade when, as a new kid at a new high school, I experienced a few instances of bullying by a certain upper classmen. Though it was more of a brief intimidation each time, the guy was significantly bigger than I was and was almost always heckling together with his jock friends. I've always been the smaller guy, and at the time I hadn't been in more than a couple of fights in my life, so I was easy to intimidate for this guy. After the second incident, I went home and started curling my guitar in its hard case, determined to do something about my size and defend myself against the likes of that guy. I guess that was my first self-motivated workout experience.\r\n\r\nFast forward to my post college years, circa mid 2011, I had gained a lot more experience of mostly body weight workouts, and I joined a dance team. After one of our practices for whatever reason I propose arm wrestling and gut punching with the other guys. Only one (Juan) was able to beat me at arm wrestling, and no one punched out my gut to stoppage. I realized I was naturally stronger than many of those guys and I liked the feeling--just about the first time in my life I had the upper hand in strength among my peers. I score a dumbell swt from my room mate, and I still work out with that set to this very day.\r\n\r\nIt would seem to me that working out has much more to do with my psyche than I realize at any given time. I work out consistently when I'm feeling good, and when I'm in that rhythm, I feel even better from day to day. What I struggle with the most is ignoring my mood and working out in spite of it, which has to happen since I'm not guaranteed a good mood everyday. There are only benefits to doing so, including improving my mood at that instant, and more importantly, keeping the rhythm of the work out habit to maintain the order of things in my life.\r\n\r\nI have more daily habits with similar issues I want to draw comparisons to, but in the interest of time and sustainable blogging I will save them for another time. Takeaway #1 to blog everyday, and #2 is to work out everyday, regardless of my mood.


