<p style=\"text-align: left;\">I recently had a conversation with two high school friends about conspiracy theories and the last days. Apparently there is a ton of new developments regarding apocalyptic events in the past few years that I was completely unaware of prior to our conversation. You can get lost keeping track of everything going on; there are so many details that could potentially apply or point to the beginnings of this or that prophecy. Hats off to those diligent enough to keep tabs. I'm not one to recognize things of this sort until they are nearly right in front of my face.<!--moreRead post--><\/p>\nIn a sense I feel it is not completely necessary for me to keep such close tabs, for a number of reasons. For one, a certain other friend of ours made a comment that once certain things are upon us, there is little we can do to prepare for them in the outward sense of sourcing food and water or amassing weapons. I do agree with that for the most part. Second, in considering the four riders of the horses in Revelation, there have always been the three negative ones running (death, famine and sickness), and they will continue to run until the end of the current age, but as a Christian my role is to consider the white horse (gospel) and opportunities for it to gain ground in the race.\n\nThat said, I do feel this type of discussion does a great job of waking me up and sobering my mind. It's all too easy to get distracted by daily necessities and the cares in the world, and to remain in that state for periods of time, and to forget about what is truly important. I do believe a Christian should live in a normal way, with longevity in mind, taking care of human resoonsibilities. But he also needs to be aware that things can change--major things--within a very short period of time, and live soberly, as if on any given day he would be taken to meet his master. That I feel I've personally neglected for quite some time and am slowly coming to grips with the reality I've always held to be true in my core. But you know what they say: admission is the first step.\n\nWith recent events occurring in the world scenario, the overwhelming theme we can see is an increased propensity for chaos and instability, with social media and the internet as a multiplier, along with subtle desensitization of our generation. I can't say that anything has happened to directly fulfill any word (if it has I don't know of it), but it's easy to see that the stage is being set for an interesting turn of events.


