title: "A New Old Friend",
date: "2016-12-22 03:07:34"
---

I have a good friend from Albania I was able to catch up with tonight. After having known him through a previous job for just over three years, tonight our conversation revealed I knew very little about him. Tonight I feel our relationship went a little further, all within a short hour and a half. After some small talk about typical things we've always bound our conversations to--who he is dating, what we have been doing at work, vacations, etc--I somehow brought up a book I am currently reading about the former Soviet Union and its labor camps.\u00a0<!--more Read post--> Having heard very little about the regime in history courses and politics, I never put together the fact that Albania was once part of it, and that my good friend actually lived through the tail end of it! You can imagine all of the questions I had for him once I found out.\r\n\r\nAfter hearing about things his family experienced before the Iron Curtain fell, we also started talking about the civil war in Albania in '97. As he was talking I felt extremely privileged to have his company, having experienced what he did and being so open to talk about it. I didn't think I would ever have had the opportunity to sit down with someone with first hand experience of that type of conflict, half a world away from me here in the priviledged US.\r\n\r\nI feel I've gotten some insight on a lesson I need to learn; that is, the value of getting to know someone beyond surface level interaction and friendship, uncovering the wealth of life experience--especially as it differs so greatly from my own--they are holding inside, consciously or not. I normally only ever put this hat of consciousness in interaction with others while I'm traveling to a new place or in some type of unfamiliar environment. In this way, I miss out on the wealth of experience of those immediately around me--I miss out. Tonight I have a new appreciation of my friend, and I hope to continue our friendship in an increasingly more meaningful way from here on.


