[caption id=\"\" align=\"alignleft\" width=\"298\"]<img class=\"\" src=\"http:\/\/assets.schwarzenegger.com\/images\/img-1.jpg\" alt=\"Pumping iron. Image from schwarzenegger.com\" width=\"298\" height=\"199\" \/> Pumping iron. Image from schwarzenegger.com[\/caption]\r\n\r\nYesterday at the recommendation of a friend, I watched\u00a0Arnold Schwarzenegger's\u00a0<em>Pumping Iron<\/em> on Netflix. Great little documentary-type film about Arnold in his prime in Mr. Olympia competitions. I heard a few interesting quotes during some of Arnold's interviews that, though shocking in some instances, I was able to take some lessons from. This post is about one of those lessons.\u00a0<!--more Read post-->\r\n\r\nI can't remember what he said\u00a0verbatim, so I'll have to paraphrase. Perhaps the most shocking thing I heard in the film was Arnold talking about his reaction to his father's death. At some point he decided to cut the world off, emotionally, so that nothing would interfere with his mindset of training to win competitions. He described it as making himself cold and emotionless, shrugging off things that would normally be quite serious. His car was stolen, so he had a secretary handle it with insurance and laughed it off, and got back to training. However, during his training for a competition, two months away, his mother called and gave him the news that his father had died, and asked if he would be coming back home for the funeral. His response was something like, \"It's too late, he's already dead; there's nothing more to be done, so I'm not going to the funeral.\" That, he said, was one of the most difficult times of his life.\r\n\r\nAn extreme case, but I do believe there is something to be said about this kind of mindset in accomplishing one's goals. I once heard a message by Ron Kangas in which he spoke briefly about sisters (women) in general being more given to feelings and emotions, while brothers (men) get stuck in their minds and logic. He then went back and said that, in some cases, however, the brothers who feel they are being logical are actually controlled by their emotions and don't realize it.\r\n\r\nWhat is really getting in the way of our following through with things we've set out to do? Is it really that unexpected situations got in the way? In my case, I want to get up everyday at 6AM to get certain things done before I go to work. I want to read the Bible, work out, and have a proper breakfast. but apparently something always happens to prevent me from getting to bed on time. The truth is, nothing is really getting in the way; if I want to sleep by 10 and get up at 6, I need to shut everything down and just do it. I've just been too controlled by how I feel at the moment, making excuses for staying up or not wanting to get up. Taking Arnold's way, I need to practice\u00a0shutting off my emotion and do what I need to do, regardless of how I feel.\r\n\r\nI do believe in the power of building up a habit of doing things you don't want to do, or want to do but don't feel like doing. On a YouTube episode, Elliot Hulse advises to do one small thing you don't want to do, every day. The human will is like a muscle that needs to be exercised and built up on a regular basis. Once you build up that muscle, or habit, it becomes easier to use. Neglect it, and it atrophies, and things become more difficult.\r\n\r\nSo actually, working out and fulfilling goals are very much related. Every day I need to ignore my feelings and get in my cold, dark garage and lift those weights. I also need to do the same with my reading, and just get it done, regardless of what else is going on. These healthy habits day after day will build up a healthy person, physically, mentally, and spiritually.


